  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Gill's Exposition of the Entire Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "But I say unto you,.... This form of speaking is used, the more strongly to asseverate the truth of what is after said; and the rather, because men are apt to indulge a liberty with their tongues; fancying no great crime is committed, when only words are spoken, and no facts done; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "that every idle word that a man shall speak, they shall give account thereof in the day of judgment. By an \"idle word\" is meant, what the Jews call, , \"light conversation\", and , \"vain discourse\", as the Hebrew Gospel of Munster reads it here; frothy language, unprofitable talk, which, though it does not directly hurt God or man, yet is of no use to speaker or hearer; and yet even this, in the last general and awful judgment, if not forgiven, and repented of, must be accounted for; and much more such horrid blasphemies the Pharisees had vented against Christ, and the Spirit of Christ. The Jews (d) have a saying pretty much like this, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "\"That even  , \"for any light conversation\", which passes between a man and his wife, he shall \"be brought to judgment\".'' ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(d) R. Jonah apud L. Capell. in loc. ",
